- name: encoding_compressibility
  rationale: |
    Random-looking sequences are those with low simple-description penalties:
    long runs, periodic templates, and imbalance.
- name: bayesian_diagnosticity
  rationale: |
    Random-looking sequences are diagnostic of a fair coin over salient
    non-random alternatives: alternating, biased, and streaky generators.
- name: inner_loop_model
  rationale: |
    People judge sequence randomness based purely on outcome frequencies, paradoxically perceiving sequences with a greater imbalance between the number of heads and tails as more random.
- name: raw_alternation_count
  rationale: |
    People perceive sequences with a higher raw count of alternations as more random, regardless of sequence length.
- name: high_alternation_rate
  rationale: |
    People judge sequence randomness based on the proportion of alternations, perceiving sequences with a higher alternation rate as strictly more random.
- name: ideal_alternation_rate
  rationale: |
    People judge sequence randomness by comparing the proportion of alternating outcomes to a subjective ideal alternation rate, perceiving sequences closer to this ideal as more random.
